ranking_subcategory: #1 of 81 things to do in Setubal
reviews/0/text: This is a huge regional park with expansive views of the water.  Great place for a long walk but beware of the hot bright sun.
reviews/1/text: This is a major reason why you come to this region.  Go to this big park and go to the beach.  Beautiful sites.
reviews/2/text: This is one of the main reasons why folks visit this region.  This is a very large park with some great views, and a good place for hiking.
reviews/3/text: There are different roads between Sesimbra and Setubal, one of them winds along the coast, along some rather high and steep cliffs. The landscape is breathtaking, especially on a sunny day: the dense vegetation of the Arrabida, the cream color of the small beaches, the turquoise of the sea and the strong blue color of the sky make a beautiful scenery. It is easy to go from Sesimbra to Setubal, but the return is not that easy as there are no signs to be found along the road, first to get out of Setubal, second to chose the right road to Sesimbra. And do not count on the indications provided by passersby: they were very few and not informed. Better use a GPS!
reviews/4/text: Founded in 1976, the park encompasses almost 70 square miles of land and sea nestled on the southernmost tip of the Setúbal Peninsula between Setúbal and Sesimbra. Our Lisbon Riders tour included several stops, allowing us to enjoy dramatic views of the stunning Portuguese coast: rocky cliffs, shimmering blue water, and long sandy beaches. This is a great day trip from Lisbon (luckily, we had beautiful weather). And don’t miss the nearby wine town of Azeitão.
reviews/5/text: Take a drive down the scenic view and enjoy the drive down the oceanic views. IT is truly spectacular. This is highly recommendable. Perfect for an afternoon drive, there are a number of coffee shops in Setubal that you can stop for a coffee and a light snack
reviews/6/text: The park is fantastic! Its nature is gorgeous! The beaches and the views are breathtaking! Strongly recommend!
reviews/7/text: Mesmerising landscape. A lot of beautiful spots. Possibility of doing paddle, canoeing or simply walk.
reviews/7/title: Breathtaking views and marvellous atmosphere. Great weather, delicious food and clear water. Woowwww
reviews/8/text:
Such nice view!!! 
Excellent view to the River and the city... 
I love the listen the birds and the wind...
reviews/9/text: A beautiful ocean views ar opening from the top of the Arrabida mountain, some of them breathtaking. Good place for hiking
reviews/10/text:
Breath taking landscape!
The color of the sea ... a mixture of green and blue. The waters are transparent. You can sea fish around you! A paradise on land!
The beaches around are worth a visit and you can go for walks and explore the rocks ...
reviews/11/text: Really nice beaches with calm water. Be sure to be on time as it can get really busy and there are not that many places to park your car. If you Arellano Felix to visit in the afternoon, it is better to make use of the shuttle busses that are operating in the area.
reviews/12/text: Beautiful natural area with beautiful views over the river Sado estuary and the Atlantic Ocean. Although we didn’t it is a great area to hike.
reviews/13/text: Walking, diving, meditating and using your camera are some of the activities you can do here. Nothing can be wrong.
reviews/13/title: beaches and blue water mixed with history and nature
reviews/14/text: Absolutely amazing! Doesn’t get any better than this... true paradise! Best place on earth, a complete hidden gem
reviews/15/text: Great walk, beautiful views. Would benefit from better signage. This is a popular route for cyclists.
reviews/16/text: It’s a very scenic car ride. Only good off the high-season, otherwise impossible to pass the traffic of sunbathers.
reviews/17/text: A must see! Huge park. Family friendly. Dress to hike. Pack water and snacks. Beautiful sights, sounds, peaceful atmosphere. Not overly run with tourists most months out of the year!
reviews/18/text: I know Arrabida since I was a little girl, my summer childhood was spent here. So I keep comming every year. The beauty of the Mountain and its beach are samething unique. Don't miss it!
reviews/19/text: We were driving from ferry bay in Setúbal towards Portinho do Arrabida to catch the sunset on one of the beaches. We were quite late, and end up driving in the sunset, in the middle of the park, climbing on and off the hills, driving on amazing serpentine-like roads full of turns, nearby the coast, with a stunning view of a pink-red sunset. Amazing experience. We will definitely do it again - perhaps on motorbikes :)

reviews/0/text:
A comfortable way to cross the sea and go to Comporta or Troia! And it doesn't take much time to get to the other side!
You can take your car with you.
Enjoyed the experience!
reviews/1/text: This beach was really lovely and had the added bonus of being able to walk across to Portinho where there are a few restaurants.  There are also some places on the beach.  Really clean beach and the water temperature wasn't too cold either!
reviews/2/text: The beach is clean and the sand is awesome. There are many places to sit down and take in the beautiful surroundings. Chill out on the beach or take a dip into the clear and calm waters. Lifeguard, toilets, restaurant on site. Car parking is cheap and the time it took to get there from out villa was worth it if only for the spectacular views.
reviews/3/text: This beach is the whitest beach I have seen in Europe. It is surrounded by lush green pine trees where birds sing. You can find beautiful pebble stones in various colours. If you want to have a swim in warm water, don't come in June or in the beginning July, though. It is freezing cold now.
reviews/3/title: Most beautiful beach besides Northern Norwegian beaches
reviews/4/text: Sort of hard to reach, making it, even more, the worth when you get there, huge beach with an actual sand area big for everyone (rare for these beaches on the mountain range) and crystal clear water where you van see the fishes, also plenty of activities available with a nice restaurant as well.
reviews/5/text:
The beaches on the Serra Arrabida are all very good and beautiful. But for us “Praia do Creiro” was the best. It´s paradisiacal and the ocean is clean and clear, great for swimming, diving and snorkeling. Or maybe just chill out!
It is very easy and inexpensive to take a public transportation from Setubal and not worrying about parking.
It´s a shame that the restaurant closer to this beautiful beach isn’t up to the standards… Very disappointing!
reviews/6/text: Man parkt etwas weiter oben für 4€. Am Strand selbst gibt es jegliche Infrastruktur, Schirm und Liegen 14€, also der übliche Preis. Wasser fällt flach ab, wenige Wellen, daher ideal für Kinder. Die Landschaft drum herum ist atemberaubend schön.
reviews/7/text: A praia continua a ser uma maravilha. Ontem a água estava com uma temperatura óptima todavia... Quando saímos, pelas 19h00, quisemos beber um café e uma Bandida do Pomar. Não me consigo recordar do nome dia bares pois estávamos lá no fundo mas fecharem às 19h???? O primeiro só disse que estava fechado, o 2o disse que tinha que ser em take away. Quando perguntei o motivo era porque encerram às 19h e abrem às 9h.. Retorqui que vivo na linha de Cascais e aqui os bares, de praia, não encerram às 19. Resposta: força. É por este tipo de atitudes que estou agira aqui a Não Recomendar nem o 1o nem o 2o bar da praia do Creiro. Lamentável. Muita falta de profissionalismo.
reviews/8/text: A praia do Creiro é fantástica! A paisagem é deslumbrante! Convém ir bastante cedo para arranjar lugar no parque.
reviews/9/text: Linda praia  da Serra da Arrábida, a última paragem do autocarro de verão. Muito fácil de chegar, já que há estrada de asfalto. Praia muito parecida com a Figueirinha.
reviews/10/text: Dajas el coche a 100 m, 4€, si llegas a tiempo. Bajas 100 m por una carretera o escaleras, playa bonita, buena arena, tienes sombrillas, sitio suficiente para ir a tu aire, tres chiringuitos (muy desiguales)
reviews/11/text:
Praia fantástica, águas cristalinas muito limpa.
O único contra é mesmo a enorme afluência a esta zona e a dificuldade para encontrar estacionamento. Apenas por esse motivo não sei se voltaria. Muito difícil estacionar. A melhor opção serão os transportes públicos, mas acaba por ser uma opção não tão prática para quem viaje no seu próprio carro.
reviews/12/text: Fomos à praia  do Creiro em um Sábado de Julho(verão). Super organizado o estacionamento, faixa de areia não mt grande, fica no meio de duas lindas montanhas verdes. Água  mt cristalina.Voltaremos com certeza
reviews/13/text:
Praia, mais para se contemplar e menos para nadar. Tem muitas pedras e o seu percurso é por vezes infernal, sendo que quase não existe parque estacionamento e o seu caminho por vezes são uns bons 5 ou 10 minutos a pé; a descer a pique e quando acabar o dia, subir a pique.
É bastante calma e sem ondas, mas no meu caso não faço questão em viver a confusão que foi até lá chegar... A um de semana, no fim de semana nem quero pensar como será.
reviews/14/text: Setúbal é linda!!!!! depois tem Praia , Serra, e Mar, estes 3 argumentos para um bom fim de semana passar em Setúbal e Tróia.
reviews/14/title: Praia do Creio, eu como setubalense para mim Praia da Arrábida, com as suas agua cristalinas e limpas, excelente
reviews/15/text: Fazendo parte do parque da Arrábida, esse pedaço de paraíso é algo esculpido. Praia agradável e com infraestrutura no verão. Se não fosse a água muito gelada, seria completo.
reviews/16/text:
Adoro,é a minha praia favorita,a paisagem é linda.
Adoro percorrer a praia,entre as rochas e o mar.
Minha praia.
reviews/17/text: Playa preciosa en un enclave único, rodeada por la Sierra de Arrábida. El acceso no es muy difícil, pero en verano no se puede visitar con coche desde Setúbal. Se puede ir en autobús desde Setúbal hasta la Praia Figueirinha, y desde ahí coger otro autobús que lleva a la Praia Do Creiro. Si se va en coche, hay que dejarlo en el estacionamiento de la Praia Figueirinha y desde ahí coger el autobús hasta Do Creiro. El autobús de ese tramo es totalmente gratuito y realiza paradas en otras dos playas más. Cuando llegas a la parada donde te deja, y donde más tarde te recoge (cada 15-20 minutos hasta 19:30 que pasa el último), hay que bajar durante 10-15 minutos hasta llegar a la playa. Pero la bajada, y luego subida, no es muy difícil.
reviews/18/text: Acesso rápido e cómodo através do autocarro disponibilizado pela autarquia, contudo, há que fazer uma caminhada até à praia. Calmo e belo.
reviews/19/text: Una playa preciosa que merece la pena visitar. Aunque no tiene un acceso tan fácil, es muy recomendable visitar esta playa y disfrutar de un día soleado en un ambiente de máximo relax.

ranking: #2 of 81 things to do in Setubal
ranking_subcategory: #2 of 81 things to do in Setubal
reviews/0/text: We visited during a tour and loved the options available. I bought fresh green grapes, cheese and tasted the ginja at a small cafe. Highly recommend buying the sheep cheese, fruits and anything else that catches your eyes.
reviews/1/text: Fish, meats, vegetables, flowers, cheeses, coffee, treats...if you need it, this market has it. Easily accessible on the Luisa Todi.
reviews/2/text: Probably the best market in the world.  Excellent produce from local farms and rivers/sea.  So much excellent choice fish, meat, vegetables, fruit, bread and cheese…  the list goes on!  You really HAVE to visit when you’re in Setubal.
reviews/3/text: This is the big covered market for the city.  I was impressed at the array of things for sale.  Food products of all sorts, of course, but there were other things such as clothes.  Nice market.
reviews/4/text: This is a very attractive market: spacious (well appreciated during the Covid pandemic when crowds should be avoided), very clean, well organized, with a wide variety of well presented products (a lot produced by the vendors themselves), with fresh fruits and vegetables, fish and seafood, meats, cheeses, delis, small restaurants including a famous vegetarian one and bottle stores selling a variety of local alcohols. It is colorful and an interesting way to discover the region.
reviews/4/title: A great way to discover the region !
reviews/5/text: A lively market, lots of great photo opps with the fish stalls,  especially if you are visiting it as a tourist like me. There were quite a few locals buying things there, so did not seem like a massive tourist trap. That said, it was hard to choose which was the best vendor to get your best produce and I'm not sure sometimes if I was being fleeced as a tourist or not. I just put it down to doing my part to help  the Portuguese economy!
reviews/6/text: It's a pretty big market, but not overwhelming. Large number of fruits, vegetables, and fish. Smaller flower section. We found the fruits/veggies to be very reasonable in cost and they tasted wonderful and fresh. We don't know enough about fish to comment on that.
reviews/7/text:
Never seen so much colour & variety of fruit, vegetables & fish in a market! Although fish prices per kilo not cheap for Portugal.
Had the cheapest coffee in all Setubal!
reviews/8/text: On our drive from Lisbon to Evora, my wife and I stopped in Setubal. While we were walking around, we briefly visited this large market located near the waterfront. From what I could see, this was a really proper Portuguese market. It was busy with local residents buying groceries—everything from fish to produce as well as some household items. Even on a Sunday morning, the market was lively with folks getting all of the groceries that they needed for (I imagine!) Sunday dinner as well as the following week.
reviews/8/title: Expansive market with fresh produce, fresh fish and so much more
reviews/9/text:
For me, this market rates as # 1
I have been and continue to go to many many markets all over the globe, mainly in Europe and North America, but there’s something very very special about this particular one. Here you have a clean, fresh and an amazing assortment of everything you would need to make anything you desire, fish being predominantly why you’re there but they have every type of meat, veggies, breads, cheeses, whines, deserts, you name it, it’s here. Do not go to Setúbal and miss the opportunity to visit the best of the best
reviews/10/text: Not only is it the coolest market ever, you can find anything your foodie heart desires plus a little. Flowers, fish, fresh fruit and vegetables. Oh and Porco Preto, do not leave without treating yourself to some of this deliciousness!
reviews/11/text: A lovely indoor market, that seems to sell, everything that you may want, food wise. Very interesting to visit, and take a look around.
reviews/12/text: We love this place! Amazing, fresh, affordable, healthy, foods. Multiple vendors. Rows and rows! Also offers jellies, jams, cheeses, chorizo, chicken, other meats, shellfish, in addition to fresh fish, octopus - pretty much anything you can think of - in addition to fresh fruits and veggies! Street parking is free. Recommendation: go early for the best selection!
reviews/13/text:
Always interesting to visit a market-hall: tge market- “ place” as a symbolic mirror of the socio- economic situation of the town- population/ of tge economic development of a town and how much importance a municipal council pays to the development of “traders.
The offer of local products( fish and meat and other foodstuffs): with delight I went on a Sunday morning through the market hall— talking to people and enjoying the market-atmosphere. A pity that there was only a modest place for having a coffee/ a drink or a small bite.
It is a place in the town center to be visited- mirroring quite well the dynamism of this town— and the apparent interest of the town- developers in improving the living standards and the infrastructure in the  formerly prestigious town center.
reviews/13/title: An inspiring pleasure to visit the market and to inhale the lively atmosphere prevailing there
reviews/14/text: The best Portuguese fish market and probably one of the best of the world. A lot of varieties of fishes and all really fresh.
reviews/15/text:
This market is an education in itself just for the variety of fish on sale - everything from salmon, dorado to swordfish and such a large assortment of different shell fish that we had not seen before.  
There is also a large selection of local produce, fruit, vegetables, cheeses and cakes.
Well worth a visit.  Go before 2 pm as it closes then.
reviews/16/text: This blew our minds I have never seen such an amazing array of seafood, veg, fruit etc. Ate the seafood at a restaurant later that day..Highly recommend!
reviews/16/title: Most amazing market I have ever seen!
reviews/17/text:
A must see in Setúbal, full of fresh fish, fruit and vegetables. You can also find meat, cheese, a café (and toilets!).

Don’t miss this if you’re in the area.
reviews/18/text: great fish market,great selection of fresh fish.the building is historical with statues and mosaics.prices are affordable.also cheese and olives are available.pretty crowded.
reviews/19/text:
Totally worth a trip here, even if you had no where to cook the fresh produces, it's a real eye opening. There's a cafe in the market that sells real good bifana, a local pork steak in a bap. 
Near by are some good restaurants. Don't forget to try the Choco frito, fried cuttlefish. seriously good..........
reviews/19/title: loads of fresh fish, fruit and veg

reviews/0/text:
To go there from Setubal via a scenic road or over Parque natural de Arrabida after visiting Cabo Espichel with the faro( light house) and convent.
The water is cold but the views are magnificent. There is parking available, a restaurant and kiosks on the beach with beds, shades and drinks.
reviews/1/text: Praia da Figueirinha is gorgeous! If you’re on the road it’s defined worthy stopping by it! It has a gorgeous view! It’s surrounded by the park and it’s a great place to take a break, walk.
reviews/2/text:
Pleasant beach!
There is a car park quite in front of the beach!
It's a nice spot where you can simply relax on the sand, go for a walk, fish ...
The sea is calm ... so you can have a swim!
reviews/3/text: The beach is lovely with white soft sand. During summer time it can get very crowded because it's not far from the city of Setúbal. Busses come all the time and bring tourists and children. If you come by car make sure to arrive before 9am otherwise you will not find a parking space (that's the reason people come by bus). The only bar-restaurant is very busy during summer time and staff get stressed. Nevertheless I recommend.
reviews/4/text:
This is by far the best beach I’ve ever been to around Lisbon! The sand was white and clean, the water was turquoise and clear, with the sun shinning in the sky above!! It was just great! And there weren’t that many people, which made it even better!!
Only problem is that it is miles away from everything, and is a good two hours away from Lisbon.
reviews/5/text: The more popular beach of the area, great location, good view of Troia across, plentiful in space, excellent parking, full restaurant with esplanade, a must check out for sure. Very popular spot!
reviews/6/text:
Sunday afternoon we went to Arrabida for the second time and we were amazed of so much beauty it was the end of June but there were not too many people to be Sunday.

The emerald color of  the water and the white color of the sand make a rainbow of superb color that we found just on the caribe.

Another amazing experience is the number of the fish around of your leg that proof the cleanliness of the water.

We hight recommended to visit Arrabida.
reviews/7/text:
I would not hesitate to award this beach as one among the most beautiful beaches in the world. The beach is very clean, and the clear blue water, aah that's amazing. You have access to changing rooms, you can rent umbrellas, and you also have a restaurant at the beach. The place is very good connected with Buses running in an interval of 30 mins to 60 mins during high season. When you travel outside of high season then there would be no buses traveling to this beach. I was there at the end of September and I needed to book a taxi to travel to this beach.

Overall an amazing experience, I would very much recommend this beach. Cheers!
reviews/8/text: This is a very beautiful, sandy beach, surrounded by mountains. The water is very clear, and deepens fast. There was a very strong current by the coast, as the mountains protected the beach from the winds, but pushed the water parallel to the coast. There are two bars on the beach, I had few good beers in one of them on a reasonable price. Even in October was few brave venturesome to swim in the ocean and quiet a few people sunbathed.
reviews/9/text: very easy to reach in comparison to the other beaches in the area, so a very good option if you want to go there by car. nioce restaurant and facilities.
reviews/10/text: Great beach frequented by all the local people. All the facilities are there. Parking difficult so get the bus. Mind the current as it gets very strong
reviews/11/text: The N 379 is stunning but you can't get into Figuerinha from the direction of Portinho da Arribada, because the road is closed during summer holidays till 7 pm !!! To get there, head to Outao and access the beach from there !
reviews/11/title: This beach is not accessible by car coming from Portinho de Arribada
reviews/12/text: Typical beach of Setúbal. beautiful with mountain above us. has restaurant, public toilettes, free showers and a lot of other activities.
reviews/13/text: Very nice beach with good access by public transportation, white clean sand, big area, wonderful temperature in Summer
reviews/14/text: Figuerinha beach at any time of the year is worth a visit. It can easily reached by car or public transport. In summer it is difficult to park and it is better to be reached by bus or taxi. The beach is large and clean with good facilities. There is a nice café-restaurant. Water is not very warm as anywhere along the atlantic coast bit doable. The view is great with the Sierra Arabida at the back. Well worth a visit
reviews/14/title: A lovely beach very close to Setubal
reviews/15/text: All of the beaches along this stretch of coast are busy and parking is often very difficult, be prepared to drive a little further onto the West Coast and you will find loads of amazing beaches that are often empty!
reviews/16/text:
Its a very nice beach close to Setubal with parking, coffee shop and all the convenient services.
It can be hard to find a place to park on summer weekends.
reviews/17/text:
Breathtaking beauty, looks like a mediterranean beach, with crystal clear waters and the rocky dark green mountains behind. The low tide creates a lagoon surrounded by sand banks

the downside
-water clear but sometimes temperature not mediterranean ("freshy")
-dificult to get a parking spot (best time is lunch hour, when some people leave)
-can get moderately crowded
reviews/17/title: A mediterranean beach in an Atlantic country
reviews/18/text: Nice enough place but a bit big and bustling for me. We did find a small rocky cove which was better.
reviews/18/title: Big beach with lots of sand, parasols, sunbeds and a couple of cafe/restaurants
reviews/19/text: Figueirinha, the largest beach in the Arrábida mountain, will amaze you with the white sand, crystal clear waters and the amazing landscape. The sea is calm and with no waves (and a bit cold). During the low tide, it is possible to walk "inside" the sea because a large portion of sand becomes uncovered. There you will have an amazing view of the beach and the mountain. Highly recommended to any beach lovers.

address: Estrada do Castelo de Sao Filipe, Setubal 2900-300 Portugal
address_obj/street1: Estrada do Castelo de Sao Filipe
description: Fortress of St. Philip An unmissable part of the tourist map, the Fortress of St. Philip was once an important stronghold for the defence and control of the city. Despite the lack of agreement among historians concerning the date its construction began, the fortress is dated to the year 1582, when King Philip II visited Setubal. The Castle of St. Philip, more frequently referred to as a fort or fortress, played a tactical role in strengthening the line of defence of the Portuguese coast that was attacked by pirates from northern Europe and Africa. Some of the most stunning panoramic views of the city and the bay can be seen from the walls of this fort.

reviews/0/text: Cool castle with great views and a small coffee shop at the top. Walking up the hill is quite a workout but it is well worth the view.
reviews/1/text: You can see this big castle from the town below, or you can take a tour by taking a taxi up the hill.  Not a good idea to do it on foot.  Impressive structure.
reviews/1/title: The Big Castle on the Hill
reviews/2/text: Hard to miss this important landmark as it is up on the hill overlooking the Bay and the city.  It is a strategic spot indeed and worth a visit.
reviews/3/text: It takes 5 minutes by car if staying in Satubal & worth the visit if only for the views. Shame hardly any information on the Fort.
reviews/4/text: The view is beautiful and the place has an inherent charm for a drink by the end of the day. Pitty that the place it is not any more a pousada (hotel), as I new it before. I hope it will became again a place where we can stay overnight.
reviews/4/title: A pleasure for the eyes and the spirit.
reviews/5/text: An amazing view of the town of Setúbal and the Troia peninsular with it's 55 kl of sandy beach.The fort also has a view of the Arrabida hills with it's windmills and pine trees. The fort is well worth a visit.
reviews/5/title: A magnificent Fort overlooking the bay of Setúbal
reviews/6/text: A place where you can just be. Look at the sea and breathe. You'll find peace there and every problem in the world will seem less worrying.
reviews/7/text:
History at its best, visited twice in the last year, April 2019 with my late wife that I miss so much and now retracing steps with our son... the place has so much history, nothing I could say changes the fact that you need to see this and all castles and fortresses throughout the entire country.
It’s a must.
reviews/8/text: This is my favorite place in the city. There is a cafe with a terrace, beautiful views. The prices are a little higher than in the city. But the interior is the best
reviews/9/text:
Sadly visited here as we were in the area. The place is very derelict, lots of graffiti and lots of rubbish littered around. 

One plus is you do get a great view from here but there are other nicer places where you can get stunning views. I won’t go back.
reviews/9/title: Quite derelict and lots of graffiti
reviews/10/text:
Our hosts in Setubal took my wife and I to see this historic structure, the original construction dating from the 1500s and newer sections added over the centuries.

The place is impressive in many ways The little chapel is ornate and gorgeous. The view from the top level is the best you'll get in Setubal. It's always nice to see a municipality where they understand what treasures deserve preservation for the public.

There's a cafe/bar on the second floor, and we enjoyed some sandwiches and drinks there.

There's room for improvement if visitors can be given more information. There are large portrait paintings in the main stairs, I have no idea who they were. I think I was able to figure out how the fortress had grown over the centuries, but some confirmation would have been nice. Where in the chapel did the perform confession or baptise? Of what use are the little parapets at the corners of some of the walls? A program to create and mount plaques in, say, Spanish, French, English and Portuguese, would make the experience so much improved.
reviews/10/title: Good free place to visit--needs some curating
reviews/11/text: Beautiful place, gorgeous setting, worth to go around sunset and have a drink. Shame that the waiters does'nt speak English, no biggie, but makes the place not very tourist-friendly. It would be nice if the place serve sparkling wine, then it became something quite memorable. It still serves cocktails, simple sandwiches. But definitely not dinner.
reviews/11/title: Beautiful setting, a most visit for Palmela
reviews/12/text: Unfortunately the weather was overcast when we visited, but I can imagine the views would be spectacular on a clear day. The lady in the tourist office was so pleasant and helpful. You can park right outside...a lot of people were parked at the gate and had a long walk in. Lovely café, church and you are allowed to explore the hotel which is beautiful.
reviews/13/text: Excellent well preserved place to visit.  Sit at the bar there and have a Moscatel of Setubal admiring the beautiful view of the city.  Be there as long as you need because you will certainly miss it.
reviews/14/text:
This is a wonderful fort with great views of Troia and the city of Setubal.
They have a esplanade that you can refresh your thirst with great service.
The prices are great, its a well spent afternoon, just for the views.
reviews/15/text: Absolutely loved wandering around this site. The walk up was a serious challenge so if you are unfit (as I am) or have mobility issues, take a car! Even though I was pretty huffy puffy when I got there, the views soon relaxed my heart rate
reviews/16/text: Great place where you besides enjoying the view can have something to eat and drink. If you have children. keep them in a short leash, some walls have o low (or none) protection.
reviews/16/title: Fort with a fantastic view over Setubal
reviews/17/text: The only cappucino we  have found in Setubal in aweek's search. For weak lungs and heavly bellies, xou can take a taxi.
reviews/18/text: Amazing View to Troia. River meets Ocean. Small Café to sit outside, to relax and enjoy for some minutes the View. To recommend.
reviews/19/text: Beautiful view and history sights all over the place. it has an amazing restaurant where we had lunch facing the city and Troia peninsula.
subcategory_ranking: #6 of 81 things to do in Setubal

description: The "House of the Bay - Center for Tourism Promotion ", is an authentic business card of the region of Setubal. The space, which functions in a building from the XVIII century, includes a tourist service area and a wine area, with a wine cellar where all the region's producers are represented. The cloisters function as a winter garden, giving support to the cafeteria where you can taste the famous muscatel of Setubal. This is the ideal space for two or a family to visit, relax and get to know better, everything Setubal has to offer.
name: Casa da Baia – Centro de Promocao Turistica

reviews/0/text: Casa da Baia has all the information you need of where to go and what to do in Setúbal, plus a wine tasting bar and entertainment in the Summer months.
reviews/1/text: We try and find the local tourist centre, when we visit a new place. This one is unique just for the building, let alone anything else. Well worth a visit.
reviews/2/text:
We wind up in a lot of tourist centers. This one is an attrraction in its own right.

First--it's got a nice courtyard lounge where you can enjoy a good drink and walk over a plexiglass floor that reveals ancient Roman ruins.

Then--you have a good wine shop and other merchandise.

The tourism office keeps it open quitre late in season, They are staffed and ready to serve.

The part I liked best was their attached dolphin museum. One room devoed to the evolution and ecology of the cetacean that generates tourism for the region. It was just right--well, i'm nuts for cetacean evolution so it could have had more for me, but for most visitors it's just right for the amount of education.

Setubal continues to impress me.
reviews/3/text: We had a great REAL gin and tonic here, perfectly done, nice atmosphere and service. the pastels were also special.
reviews/4/text: We visited out of season so the house was not running full tilt but it is original and pleasant, excellent for cooling down, and the people are nice, helpful and nonaggressive.
reviews/5/text: Kind of tourist centre in a very beautiful old-house setting with plenty of info about Setubal (visits, tours, etc.) and options for tasting local food and drinks, specially the Setubal MOSCATEL wines
reviews/6/text: I was expecting to see more, but I enjoyed the shop where you can buy many different brands of local wine. The most interesting part concerns dolphins and you can read about the various sorts of dolphins. It will take you less than 20 minutes.
reviews/7/text:
The staff here are extremely helpful. They are able to provide you with a map of Setúbal and give you a list of “ must go” places in the town.
Also a great place to relax with a glass of wine
reviews/8/text: The Casa da Baia has been very well restored. However it would appear that the service is done by employees of the town. Difficult to get a cup of coffee or otherwise. Better to lease it to a private caterer. But well worth a visit to see the restauration
reviews/8/title: Very nice place, but poor service
reviews/9/text:
a wide range of local production is available here. Nice relation quality/price and very good offer variety.
You can also relax in the space and try some of the local jewels in order to decide what to take.
reviews/9/title: a place to buy local products
reviews/10/text: This is a great hub of information, refreshments, outdoor space and cultural exhibits.  The staff are incredibly friendly and helpful - if they don't know an answer, they will look it up online for you.  Also a port in the storm if you are in need of a restroom.
reviews/11/text:
I came here with a friend who lives in this town. They offer local and regional products. 
The selection of Moscatel de Setúbal and Moscatel Roxo is wide. 
There is also a place in the back to sit and enjoy the Moscatel. It is built on the top of Roman ruins.
reviews/12/text: Top. For a good relax time with friends, family or alone. Plenty of spots to seat with different deccors. Fair offer in the bar, a nice gourmet store and wines side by side. Outdoor seats available. Roman ruins visible. Easy parking close by. A must go!
reviews/13/text: Friendly staff working at the info center with very good english assistance. They lady gave me a nice map of Setubal and guided me towards the places I wanted too see. They also gave me some good recommendations of other places to see in Setubal.
reviews/14/text: Casa da Baía is a bit of everything: it's a bar (with nice prices) with covered and outside areas to sit and enjoy, as well as a place where you find a bit of the local culture and where you can buy local wines and hand-made items from Setúbal. There are also areas with small exhibitions of local culture things.
reviews/14/title: Great cultural and quiet bar in Setúbal's city centre
reviews/15/text: With the recent interior works, the House of Bay, turned into a place that all the turist must visit. It's composed with an exhibition room, a wine bar, that have several wines from the region, and a gourgeos outside space, that's very confortable, and an inner cloister that's well decorated. An huge wall painting of a turtle, and several other areas around. In all the House of Bay is a spectacular place, for who want to learn more about our region.
reviews/16/text: This place hides a little bar with an excellent Setùbal moscatel (2€ per glass), and a nice back court to enjoy your drink on a sunny day!
reviews/17/text:
It includes a wine area with a wine cellar in which they are represented 36 producers in the region, able to receive specialized events of this economic activity, and a gourmet shop with cheeses and traditional sweets.

Space also work an exhibition gallery with temporary exhibitions of municipal responsibility, a multi-purpose auditorium, a meeting room and space for the brotherhoods of Azeitão cheese and Moscatel for the Association Bay of Setúbal and tour promoters, and several breakout rooms.

The House Bay, authentic living room Setubal region also includes the Municipal Tourist Office, with areas of service and an area of ??administrative support.

The Cloisters, an area now fully covered, works as a winter garden, a space dedicated to moments of conviviality and pleasure, suitable for holding small cultural events.

Outdoor, one of the outdoor areas that make up the property, was created another play area and shows that through the ground glass, allows us to observe archaeological remains discovered at the site during the phase of preparation of the site. Some of these findings are exhibited in a small museum created for this purpose.

The creation of the House of Bay also allowed refunctionalization of a building of the first half of the eighteenth century and classified as Municipal Heritage.

The work included in PIVZRS - Integrated Programme for the Enhancement of riverfront Setubal area with costs of around one million euros, was executed with contribution of EU funds through the PORLisboa - Regional Operational Programme of Lisbon, under the NSRF - National Strategic Reference.
reviews/17/title: House Bay The House Bay - Tourism Promotion Centre, inaugurated on May 7, 2011,
reviews/18/text: Unlike other commentators this was actually our last stop in Setubal rather than our first.  We would up finding the place as we saw posters of a Moscatel and candied orange tasting (with no location on it) and asked around until we found it.  The "tasting" was a little disappointing as you got one sip of one Moscatel and a slice of candied orange.  There were a lot of other wines for sale, but no basis for assessing how they tasted.  Although everyone was polite, I wouldn't say they were warmly welcoming to foreign visitors.
reviews/18/title: A good starting point for Setubal - if you can find it
reviews/19/text: This is the “tourist Information” located on the "Avenida Luisa Todi" where we went to inform us on what we should visit in Setubal. And we were more than surprised of the dedication of the person behind the desk, he really took his time to explain everything in detail on a map and you could see that he was really enjoying his job, we like to thank us once again for his perfect information. This is the place to e for the tourist who likes to visit Setubal.

reviews/0/text: Fabulous, the weather super 30c. Virtually empty when we arrived. Maybe not enough parking for high season. Just a lovely large beach, allowing access along the coast!!!
reviews/1/text:
I grew up here, this has always and will always be my backyard… 
There is something very special here that I can’t duplicate anywhere else in the world. When growing up, we all dreamt about the Pacific and now that I live in the Pacific Northwest, all I want is to go back to my beloved Sado
reviews/1/title: The love of my life 3rd generation
reviews/2/text: It is a paradise beach. Access and parking may be difficult. The descent to the beach doesn't help either, but it's worth it. Perhaps one of the best beaches in the world...
reviews/3/text: Beautiful beach but a big problem to park the car. Far too little parking space. The water is very calm and crystal clear.
reviews/4/text: I'm going to this  beach since I was a little boy (70's) ... unfortunately in our days to much tourists ... but still one of the must beautiful beach
reviews/4/title: Imagine be there with no more than 100 persons
reviews/5/text:
Breath taking views in a great location, making you feel being in an exotic location worldwide.
Access only via buses as cars not allowed in protected area, making this feel even more exotic.
Ensure you have a drink at the bar on the swinging chair while enjoying the beautiful sunset.
reviews/6/text: PLEASE DO NOT PARK BY THIS BEACH IF YOU HAVE A RENTAL CAR!!! Our car was broken into and all our luggage was taken even though we were parked next to lots of other cars right by the main road. Nothing was visible (luggage was in the boot) but people target rental cars and smash the windows. It is not safe to park by these beaches and the police did not seem surprised when we reported the crime in Setubal. Please do not risk it as it is not safe even though it looks like it is.
reviews/6/title: RENTAL CAR BROKEN INTO - DO NOT PARK HERE!
reviews/7/text: Amazing view and beach, I love coming here to photograph and relax, for those who visit Lisbon try and get a day to come here, you won't regret, and the food is also amazing
reviews/8/text: Galapinhos beach was definitely a hidden gem! It was the most beautiful beach that we had seen around Serra da Arrábida! It’s surrounded by the park and its nature! It has a gorgeous view! Definitely worthy seeing it!
reviews/9/text: Absolutely stunning. Clear transparent waters. Nature all around. Great hot sunny weather. A special place!
reviews/9/title: I loved the water and the surrounding nature. Absolutely incredible.
reviews/10/text:
I loved this beach.
The water is low, transparent and quite warm. 
A good spot to relax, go for a walk and explore!
reviews/11/text: Been going here for the vast majority of my life. This is by far the hidden gem  of the Arrabida beaches, this one and “Coelhos” next door... both require you to hike and that’s the reason that still to this day, they retain the privacy and its beauty. No matter what month it is, what the weather is doing, where exactly in the world I am, my heart’s  always here 100%
reviews/12/text:
Amazing and beautiful beach! One of the most beautiful in Europe! 
The ocean is a bit cold but even that, if you come to Lisbon you can't miss, is just about 50 kilometres.
reviews/13/text: We arrived at the beach and found parking in the paid area very easy to negotiate. 5E for the day. Caught the shuttle, free, but walked the short distance back. Gorgeous beach, walked down the rough track easily to find only a small number of people compared with other beach spots. No children because of the inconvenience of carrying items down the hill. You can easily walk to the next beach where there are more facilities. Water was COLD! but then the Atlantic Ocean is cold. Lovely day and worth the drive and walk.
reviews/14/text: With the city bus (€4,15 retour) you can go to the beaches of the Arrabida area. The bus stops at Fighuerina beach, and from there, there is a free shuttle bus to the other beaches. We went to Galaphinos beach, a relaxed cosy beautiful beach. There is a simple bar where you can buy refreshments. The Arrabida area is most visited by Portugese people, what gives it a local atmosphere.
reviews/15/text:
We stopped at this spot during a road trip to Alentejo, to spend the day at the beach! 
It has an amazing surroundings and the sea was amazing to refresh, the beach was with limited access by car but there is a free shuttle who take people - it runs every 20min
reviews/16/text:
This is a must go, the beauty of this place is breathtaking. It was names the best beach in Europe in 2017 probably because of it´s soft sand, the seas blue shades and tranquility. To arrive there from Lisboa, you should take a train to Setubal, the a bus to Praia da Figueirinha, from there you can take a shuttle or about a 2 km hike. 
Once there you can rent a beach chair with an umbrella. There is a place that sells drinks. You will see some boats that spend the day there. 

I really wirthwhile the trip, if you are in Portugal a must see..
reviews/17/text:
Firstly, it’s so so difficult to park because car parking is so small and road is so stretch. Police is checking if cars are ok.
Once there you got two beaches to choose, Galapinhos and Creiro.
If you choose Galapinhos you have to walk through a hard path to reach the sand and, maybe in the past it was the best beach in Europe but now it’s just a beach with not so much people
reviews/18/text: Beautiful and very clean beach with nice services. We arrived by car and there were a lots of cars waiting to get in the parking area, but within 10 minutes we got in. And surprisingly half of day parking costed only €2,80!
reviews/19/text: Wow this beach is so nice. Recommend to be really early though for parking  but the beach is super nice!

reviews/0/text: A beautiful beach with clear water and lovely scenery. the water is cold in the summer but very chilling. The beach has a restaurant, bar and umbrellas and a shower for a price. With the rocky side of the beach and the moderate crowd, I would say one of the best in the world.
reviews/0/title: It is definitely worth the visit
reviews/1/text: Great beach, beautifull water colors, but please make sure to bring your pic nic basket as the restaurants there arent really anything special.
reviews/2/text: We parked at Figueirinha beach (road closed so couldn't go any further and walked to Galapos. It is only a 20 minute walk and was very pretty, better than getting the shuttle bus. Because of this logistic, the beach wasn't too busy. The beach is backed by rolling green hills, was very clean and the waters crystal clear. The beach restaurant however wasn't great (food average and quite pricy and the toilets and restaurant very shabby) and so I recommend taking a packed lunch.
reviews/2/title: Soft sand, crystal waters and not too many people
reviews/3/text: The beach is nice, but now that big. Although you can walk to other beaches (but be careful). The sand is a little bit big corny and in the water you sink fast with your feet in it (Not alarming though). The water goes deep pretty fast.
reviews/4/text:
Amazing  beach , amazing clear water, amazing views , i hope people won't ruin it!
The only downside is that theres is no car park , you have to park on the side road , and walk but is definitely worth the walk !
reviews/5/text: We had a nice walk along the beach, which has a cafe and an old derelict villa, such a shame, it would be a lovely spot.
reviews/6/text: One of the smallest Arrábida beaches, but easily one of the most beautiful! Less wind than in Figueirinha, less strong tides and less parking spots and a better beach bar is what you may expect here, apart from the beautiful landscape! Just lay back and enjoy!
reviews/7/text: Great beech very clean and family friendly. Not too many people or it didnt seem like it as the beech was vast. Great little bar on the beech too
reviews/8/text:
Desde lado de Setúbal e no rio sado uma das minhas praias preferidas, águas límpidas e ambiente a natureza da serra de um lado e o rio/ mar do outro
muito bom
reviews/9/text:
Mon p'tit coin de repos,le vrai . Comme toutes les plages de la Serra da Arrabida en été, pas de voiture. Exception faite pour Figueirinha, mais bonne chance pour trouver une place de parking en plein été.
Des bus jaunes sont mis en place pour accéder aux plages, le ticket pris dans le bus coûte 2,60€ l'aller et autant pour le retour. Astuce, acheter une carte de transport (0,50€) à la gare routière. Elle est rechargeable et le trajet vous coûte alors moitié prix. Infos sur le site Carris Metropolitana.
Bref, Galapos se fait voler la vedette par Galapinhos, qui n'est rien d'autre que la moitié droite de cette même plage. 
Plage propre, mer calme, bar restaurant Ondagalapos , sanitaires mis à disposition, transats à louer et espace parasol. Paddle sur place.
reviews/10/text: A viagem até à praia e contemplar a paisagem. As águas cristalinas, a areia, as montanhas e o asseio.
reviews/11/text:
Envolvida pela deslumbrante paisagem da Serra da Arrábida, a Praia de Galapos é uma das mais bonitas da região, está abrigada pelas arribas que a protegem de ventos, mantendo a tranquilidade das suas águas.

Ao lado de Galapos, encontramos a mais selvagem e escondida praia dos Galapinhos que também conta águas calmas e transparentes, tendo sido já eleita como a melhor praia da Europa.
reviews/12/text: Ein toller Strand! Im Herbst 2020 auch super leer. Aber das ist vermutlich in anderen Jahren/ Jahreszeiten nicht so. Nette kleine Bar.
reviews/13/text:
Al ser nombrada una de las playas más bonitas de Europa esperábamos algo más. Desde luego es un entorno natural muy bien conservado y respetado,  y hacen una fantástica labor al comunicarse únicamente en autobús para evitar atascos y problemas mayores pero el paisaje en sí es muy semejante a las pequeñas calas de las rias baixas, no me resultó tan sorprendente como esperaba.
Al ser pequeña puede estar muy llena de gente
reviews/14/text: A praia é ótima e tem uma ótima paisagem,todavia possui uns acessos que são bastante complicados que não é recomendável a pessoas com uma idade mais avançada.
reviews/15/text: Extraordinária!!! Águas calmas e cristalinas super convidativas a um mergulho! Estrutura de bar com mesas e guarda sol! Não tem como ser ruim. Arrias fininhas e branquinhas.
reviews/16/text: abbiamo trascorso una giornata all'insegna del relax, buon cibo, acqua del mare pazzesca e facilissima da raggiungere grazie allo shuttle gratuito che ti porta lungo le spiagge
reviews/17/text: A praia é linda, é uma das minhas praias favoritas. Pequeno paraíso de Portugal, recomendo a visita!
reviews/18/text: Uma das praias mais interessantes da Arrábida é sem dúvida a Praia dos Galapos,com boa praia e boa paisagem.
reviews/19/text: Mais uma praia lindíssima. o único se não é a falta de estacionamento, apesar de ter autocarros a custo zero  é difícil arranjar estacionamento, podemos estacionar no parque que existe mas é muito pequeno e cobram 4€ o dia.

reviews/0/text: Even during the week the walk is long if you do not come super early... there is not sufficient parking and as the beach is in the natural reservoir there is police not letting people drive further a certain point.... however, even after long walk down the hill we have managed to arrived and enjoyed the day on this pleasant beach... it has a bit Mediterranean look, is warmer and the water is very calm
reviews/1/text: This is a long lovely beach with perfect soft sand. It is a great place for sun and sea - or just for a long stroll like we did.
reviews/2/text: Very calm and peaceful beach away from the crowds. The water is calm. It is surrounded by the mountains. Very picturesque.
reviews/3/text: For me it's my favorite beach in Setúbal. The problem is the access that is very complicated but if you are able to find the right path you will love it. It a small beach but they view and the peace that you will find here it's worth it
reviews/4/text: Will have to walk down gravel path of shrubs for about 10-15 min - but well worth the effort- calm, beauty...
reviews/5/text: Small and definitely one of the most difficult to access (since you have to cross by foot a part of the mountain following a non-easy trail from the road), but definitely worthwhile. You can take photos of the beautiful surroundings along the way and once there you'll never want to leave, since it will give you the idea that you're in an island with a private beach for you (and, granted, all the other people there...). Simply amazing!
reviews/6/text:
Just be prepared getting to the beach is not easy. As you have to follow a dubious mountain track. 
Water usually rather coldish. 
In summer go early morning for total peace and quite.
reviews/7/text: I love this beach.be prepared for a hike down.but it is worth the hike.maybe a 15 min.walk,parking is difficult to find but again worth the effort.beach is small and beautiful.nice little coves to swim into and explore.be ready to see nude tourist.everyone who visits setubal should find this beach and relax!worth every effort.
reviews/8/text: Bring your SUP or kayak, you will love the beach!!! Last weekend there were some stones as you would enter to the water...strange. Its a lovely beach, small but neat! Make sure to bring umbrella, sunblock and enough water. Be ready to walk from the car to the beach, in high season it might be croweded so avoid weekend traffic and get early.
reviews/9/text: Parece una cala típica de  Baleares o incluso de Tailandia. El ambiente es tranquilo y las vistas preciosas, con aguas azul turquesa y rocas en los lados. Además al tener un valle detrás, da el sol hasta bien entrada la tarde.
reviews/10/text: No está indicado, debes caminar por una ladera y la playa non tiene servicios, pero es una playa espectacular, de arena muy fina y agua transparente. Quizá un poco fría, si.
reviews/11/text: Mais uma boa praia na Arrábida ,esta,contudo mais pequena e com os acessos um pouco mais difíceis,mas uma maravilha.
reviews/12/text: Uma praia excelente mas de difícil acesso. Quando a maré está baixa pudemos lá ir através da Praia de Galapinhos.
reviews/13/text: Praia de excelencia, aguas transparantes e calmas, ausencia de vento, dada a sua localizacao, paisagem deslumbrante.
reviews/14/text:
Très belle plage au cœur du parc naturel de Arrabida. Oui l'eau est "froide" mais c'est le cas sur toute la côte Portugaise. L'eau est transparente, de quoi voir quelques poissons le long des rochers. Une petite grotte sympa à visiter sur la droite de la plage quand on regarde vers la mer.

Important à savoir, la route entre la plage do Creiro et la plage da Figueirinha est fermée en été (je ne connais pas les dates exactes). Pour accéder à la plage dos Coelhos, se garer au parking de la plage do Creiro. Il faut y arriver tôt car le parking est complet des 10h. L'accès à la plage est à 3 min en partant du parking vers la route fermée à la circulation. Compter environ 10 minutes de descente avec des enfants.

Autre possibilité, plus facile pour le stationnement mais plus long (environ 1h entre l'arret de bus et l'arrivée à la plage) se garer à Setubal puis prendre le bus (ligne 723, 723A ou 725) qui vous amènera à la plage da Figueirinha. (Compter 4,20€ le billet aller retour pour adulte et 2,1€ pour les enfants). Prendre ensuite la navette gratuite (une tous les 1/4 d'heure), s'arrêter à l'arrêt plage Galapinhos, monter 3 min à pied le long de la route pour trouver le chemin descendant à la page de Coelhos.
reviews/15/text: Fantastisk strand der du kan finne deg en liten privat plass mellom steinene. Etter du har parkert kan man gå ut på stranden og ta til venstre og finne en litt mer privat plass
reviews/16/text: è dos istios que a fotografia corresponde ao que se observa no local pode ir por terra ou de barco uma praia fantástica
reviews/17/text: Pequena praia meio escondida e de acesso para os mais persistentes. Uma das praias menos procuradas da Arrábida e, por isso, mais sossegada e tranquila. A água fria e cristalina não assunta ninguém.
reviews/18/text:
Está justo al lado de la famosa Galapinhos, pero es muy bonita también.
Suele haber menos gente que en las otras calas, porque el acceso es incluso más difícil que en Galapinhos.
Preciosa, como sus hermanas del Parque Natural.
reviews/18/title: Cala pequeña, de acceso dificilísimo y casi desierta
reviews/19/text: praia de difícil acesso, convém algum espírito de aventura para seguir os diversos trilhos que estão pelo meio da serra e dar com o certo para se chegar ao areal, praia não vigiada mas com o mar muito calmo e com zona de "pé" pelo mar dentro.

reviews/0/text:
I stumbled onto Praia do Portinho by chance on a previous visit and just had to return. The beauty of the place is captivating, almost out of a movie - recommend 110% if in the area of Setubal. 

You won’t be able to take you car directly to the beach and the directions provided by google maps is wrong. Instead of driving along the coast (coming from Setubal), go direction Sierra da Arrabida.

Make sure to stop along the way in any of the view points at the Sierra, the views are incredible.

Once you get to the entrance to Portinho there will be a guard, park wherever you can and walk down (about 10mins) or for €2-€3 you can ride down on tuk tuk’s that operate for most of the day. 

Once you get to Portinho, you can enjoy a meal at any of the restaurants or just chill at the beach. I believe there a boat rides that operate from there but we never booked any.

Setubal is know for its fried cuttlefish so make sure to try them at any of the restaurants located there, best I’ve ever had!
reviews/1/text: Tranquil little place accessed over a short, very steep and narrow road with a couple of restaurants All with splendid view over the bay. Only drawback is the limited parking
reviews/2/text:
It's a short walk from the village to reach the beach. Freezing water, windy as usual in the region.
The water colour and silence plus good food at D'u Portinho (Esplanada Bar seems to be the old name) make it excellent place to visit.
reviews/3/text:
The beach is beautiful with really clear waters. The access is very complicated. We stopped the car on the side of the road near a restaurant called Mafalda and walked all the way down to the beach.
There is a traffic light controlling the traffic in and out the beach which might cause some traffic on the high season.
All restaurants were full. Maybe it is a good idea to make reservations. We couldnt get seated anywhere.
Services seem not prepared for the amount of people in there. Hope it gets better in the summer.
Will come back to check cause the beach is really awesome and the village charming.
reviews/4/text: A beautiful little port situated inside the Arrabida National Park in Portugal. The port is very tranquil and relaxing it has three restaurants all serving speciality fish dishes with locally caught fish and seafood. Prices are not exorbitant and portions are substantial. The view is very beautiful and the port is a short walk to the Pria Creiro which is a wide sandy beach with calm sea that is very clean. The only downside is the carpark is very small and in high summer you might have a long walk to the port but the restaurants lay on a free bus if you book a table in advance.
reviews/4/title: Pria do Portinho my favourite beach in Arrabida

reviews/6/text:
It´s a perfect location for someone loving quiet beaches and clear water ocean. As it´s of difficult access it isn’t too crowded; inserted in beautiful and bucolic surroundings it seems like a small paradise. Full of maritime life and lots of hiking and diving opportunities.
Water shoes are important because a good part of the beach is a bit rocky. 
Waterproof camera is a nice to have for great photo chances.
reviews/7/text: Set in a beautiful Natural Park, hidden away in a small bay is a fantastic beach with crystal clear water. Lots of small marine life, starfish, jellyfish, anemones, fish, sea snails, shells, sea weed just perfect for snorkeling or scuba. There are a couple of restaurants but I havent tried them. The beach is mostly sand but there are some areas with rocks, I recommend the use of water shoes to protect the feet not just because of the rocks but also because of urchins, specially for children. You need to go early as not that much parking available. After you park the shuttle will take you to the beach, I believe it runs from 9am and its every 20 minutes otherwise you can walk, its only a few minutes and you can hear the cicadas singing whilst you walk down.
reviews/8/text: small, beautiful beach with some charming houses. bucolic place. The local restaurants are not as good as they once were, maybe because it was not season.
reviews/9/text: This is one of the best beaches between Lisbon and Setubal. It is hard to access during weekends beacause they close the road for cars.
reviews/10/text: Lovely place with very nice, wild beach and landscapes. Very fine sand. Everything is great except there are little stones at the entrance in the water
reviews/11/text: Cuesta un poco acceder a ella, pero el intento merece la pena. Lugar muy bonito, playa tranquila rodeada de sierra y aguas limpísimas.
reviews/12/text: L'eau est tellement transparente avec des nuances de bleues turquoises...un vrai plaisir pour les yeux!!! A faire !!!
reviews/13/text: Praia de eleição para quem procura uma praia enquadrada entre a serra e o mar, Pequeno cais com restaurantes e atividades marítimo-turísticas.
reviews/14/text: A praia é bonita, estando o acesso cortado a veículos automóveis na época balnear é uma caminhada de 30 a 40 minutos. Se pensa ir nesta altura aproveite para levar almoço e lanche para o dia ou comer no restaurante que se encontra localizado no caminho e descansa um pouco da caminhada até a praia. Cuidado com as rochas na praia, deve levar sapatos para andar na água.
reviews/14/title: Lugar bonito mas de difícil acesso
reviews/15/text: Para chegar você seguirá por uma estrada  ingreme e com lindas vistas. Uma pequena ponte liga a estrada a pequena Praia do Portinho. Existem dois restaurantes com preços razoaveis no local. O estacionamento no Portinho é pequeno, por isso tem que ir cedo , deve caber no maximo uns 50m carros. É uma visita rapida, de no maximo 1 hora.
reviews/16/text:
Água limpida, verdadeiramente azul e calma.
A praia é pequena mas é realmente muito bonita.
Óptimos acessos quer de carro quer a pé.
reviews/17/text: Traumhaftes Plätzchen Erde, eine entzückende Bucht. Leider etwas kompliziert zu erreichen, da der Ort für den Autoverkehr gesperrt ist in der Saison. Und der Strand ist leider steinig, kein reiner Sandstrand. Aber sehr sehenswert und mit tollen Restaurants direkt am Wasser.
reviews/18/text: On peut y passer un très agréable moment en début de saison (après le parking est compliqué pour cause de "surpopulation" touristique le détour vaut largement le coup et le poisson grillé servi dans les petits troquets sur place est des plus savoureux.
reviews/19/text: A praia é pequena mas muito bonita. A água é límpida, a paisagem fenomenal. O melhor que a Serra da Arrábida tem para oferecer.

reviews/0/text: We walked a long distance along this major street looking for some life.  We found a place to eat and off of it we found a pleasant neighborhood.  But on the whole, the street was not that pretty.
reviews/1/text: We took a walk on this wonderful avenue. Good stores, restaurants and you can make your way up to the castle of Sam Felipe.
reviews/2/text: A beautiful avenue with a few typical restaurants. Certainly not to be missed is a visit to the covered market. Probably the best in Portugal when it comes to fish.
reviews/2/title: Beautiful central avenue from the harbour to the Arrabida
reviews/3/text: We walked a long distance along this broad city avenue looking for a place to eat.  There is a stone walking area in the center along with a fountain at the city center  Shops and cafes along the edge and some views of the port.
reviews/4/text: This market has a reputation of being the best in Europe. There is always a great variety of freshly caught fish and the market is very unusual with it's murals of typical, Portuguese tiles. Local cheeses are quite delicious especially fresh sheep or goats cheeses. When you visit the market don't forget to look out for Bloomy Market, preparing and making healthy vegetarian meals on the premises with a view into the main market.
reviews/4/title: Setúbal´s well known fruit and vegetable market-
reviews/5/text:
An avenue where you will find everything:
Restaurants, theawtre, supermarcket, cafés, museums, statues, parks and whatever you  wish for.
reviews/6/text: To many good things to say in such a small space. The options here are endless, anything and everything to do you’ll find it here, parks, shops, restaurants, fountains, amusement, you name it, this is the place to be if your visiting Setúbal. You can spend a day just walking up one side and down the other visiting the different locations within the Avenue, including the Livramento market. Enjoy
reviews/7/text: A lovely area, with a green belt down it. The street is busy, but still, its a lovely area to walk down. Well worth a visit.
reviews/8/text: Beautiful, colourful and impressive buildings with lots of entertaining street art and sculptures and lots of cafes. fountains, and flowers. Wandering from one end to the other was a very pleasant way to spend a few hours.
reviews/9/text: By far the best traffic solution of any city i ever visited.Not a queue i saw in a week. Also shady and pleasant.
reviews/10/text: It is a very busy street, but the green belt in the middle of it gives the street a certain old style look. You can read a book or just observe because the Portuguese do not speak very loud.
reviews/11/text: With open bars and a fresh vegetation environment it's one of the top Setubal spots to take a hike and stroll around
reviews/12/text: I was with a tour group and we were given some time on our own to explore Setubal; it was a total surprise and not on our itinerary.  I was impressed with the architecture, the shops, the restaurants and overall happy vibe to the town.  There were visiting Spanish tuna singers in town so we were treated to some great vocals as they strolled through the streets.
reviews/12/title: Enjoyed this main bouvelard that borders the riverfront
reviews/13/text: The avenue has several highlights like Livramento market dated 1876 with marvellous blue tiles and more than a dozen fish restaurants together with special fried cuttlefish
reviews/14/text: The Avenue stretches along the riverfront, and affords lovely views of the port and ferry area to the left, the sandy outline of Troia straight ahead, and the interesting coves to the right that lead in the direction of Sesimbra.
reviews/15/text: Setubal has a unique wide avenue, almost like a park in the centre. There are plenty cafés and restaurants too. Cycling is also possible with a dedicated path. Architecture is typically Portuguese with a few nice buildings
reviews/15/title: Quite a unique avenue for a nice stroll
reviews/16/text: nice place. in the city. lovely walk way and places. a lot to see. nice cafe, shops, resturants. colourful area. vibrant places.
reviews/17/text:
Very long avenue in the center of the city 
Nice place to have w walk after lunch or dinner and relax a bit
reviews/17/title: Good place to have a walk
reviews/18/text: Majestic Avenue (  Avenida) and surroundings, old historical constructions are well preserved, with in stone structures and modern day construction side by side without spoiling the sentiment of old times. Cafe, restaurants and typical Portuguese pubs are available on both side of the avenue. Beautiful
reviews/19/text: Well maintained avenue in the middle of Setubal. The surrounding area is well looked after and definitely a good place for a walk. Lots to see on this avenue.

reviews/2/text: We visited briefly early evening in the hope of seeing flamingos. The tide was out so flamingos were only just visible on the horizon however there were plenty of smaller birds to look at. A pair of binoculars or a telescope for visitors would have been helpful. Having said that this is a gorgeous peaceful spot for an early evening drink. A large stylish terrace with comfortable seating and chilled wine and beer available. Parking is easy and interesting metal bird sculptures to admire to compensate for not seeing real ones. Serious bird watchers probably have good advice on the best times to see birds.
reviews/3/text: Not far from Alcochete, a good base for the Evoa and Salinas do Samouco refuges, this looked promising. I went on a Monday. The restaurant was closed. The tide was out. I would love to post lots of photos showing flocks of wading birds but I saw next to nothing. Maybe I was unlucky . . .
reviews/4/text: Highly recommend if you are visiting the city, specially in the summer. Try to find a tour operator and you will love the view of the bay and all the variety that Sado River as to offer you.
reviews/5/text: Según la marea esté baja o alta cambia el paisaje, es interesante y un lugar de gran valor para los amantes de la ornitología.
reviews/6/text: A une dizaine de km de Setubal, la réserve ornithologique de l'estuaire du Sado. Entre la visite de l'ancien moulin à eau et la ballade en bateau, comptez 2 à 3 heures, mais vraiment ça vaut le coup. C'est l'endroit ou je vais quand j"ai besoin de décompresser ! La ballade en bateau vous fera découvrir suivant la saison une multitude d'espèces d'oiseaux. Le guide est adorable, il vous fournira les jumelles et vous commentera avec plaisir la visite.
reviews/6/title: Une ballade à ne pas louper !
reviews/7/text: Taxival mentünk setubali szállásunkról. 18 euro volt a számla négyünknek. Szép a part, minimális, de elég szolgáltatás van. A f? baj az volt, hogy embertelenül hideg volt a tenger, mintegy 18-19 fokos csak. Bementem nehezen a vízbe, mintha jeges t?kkel szúrkáltak volna. Mikor végre belemerültem teljes testtel, akkor a t?k elmúltak, ám a jeges érzés megmaradt. Viszont a leveg? h?mérséklete 35 fok volt! Érdekes volt, hogy a part mellett olyan er?s volt a víz sodrása, mintha gyors folyóba merült volna az ember. Ez kés? délutánra elmúlt, mert jött a dagály. Én meg mentem. Busszal vissza a szállásomra.
reviews/8/text: bom espao para passear e observar aves, recomendo ir com bom tempo e preparado para o dia todo, snacks etc
reviews/9/text: L'estuario del fiume Sado inizia vicino ad Alcácer do Sal, una zona fertile e umida, dove si trovano anche campi di riso. Ci sono ciarca duecento specie di uccelli che popolano l'estuario del Sado comprese cicogne bianche di cui si vedono i nidi appollaiati in cima alle torri delle chiese.e per il suo valore naturalistico l’estuario è stato dichiarato Riserva Naturale e zona di protezione per le specie. C'è anche una colonia di delfini nel fiume Sado e vengono organizzate gite in barca per osservarli. La vegetazione comprende querce da sughero, pinete, i cui pinoli vengono usati nei dolci regionali, e le saline ormai dismesse ma che erano di grande importanza economica nei secoli. Bella zona da esplorare.
reviews/10/text: Siamo andati probabilmente nel giorno sbagliato. C'erano pochi uccelli e molto fango. Sicuramente in una giornata di sole avrebbe fatto un'altra impressione
reviews/10/title: Non in un giorno umido e piovoso
reviews/11/text: Forse non era il periodo migliore ma sinceramente non mi è sembrato poi così speciale. Mi ha fatto anche tristezza vedere quel pezzettino di oasi nel mezzo a tanto sporco e circondato da ciminiere di industrie e centrali elettriche; forse avremmo dovuto pensarci prima? Che peccato
reviews/12/text: Estuário lindíssimo. Mas pertencendo a responsabilidade à  entidade estatal que quase sempre torna esta reserva natural um local pouco aprazível...não fosse a Natureza por si só a fazer esse papel.
reviews/13/text:
Zona muito calma, com paisagens deslumbrantes e grande diversidade natural.
Ideal para quem gosta de locais calmos e desfrutar da natureza.
Percursos acessíveis, bem sinalizado e documentado.
reviews/14/text: Reserva e Beleza Impar, animais e Aves diversificados. Uma atenção especial para os Passeios Maritimos e a possibilidade de observar Golfinhos em perfeita ligação com a Natureza.
reviews/15/text: Na Herdade das Mouriscas,  pode-se fazer uma viagem de barco à Reserva Natural do Estuário do Sado. Vale a pena para observar toda a fauna existente ali, desde flamingos a garças. De salientar que não deve deixar de visitar a Casa Baia também na Herdade das Mouriscas.

reviews/16/text: Estuário cuidado, desassoreado, com tráfego de ferry´s e katamarans para Tróia, e imensos barcos  para o turista  percorrer todo o estuário e visitar os golfinhos, que nem sempre se deixam ver.
reviews/16/title: Estuário onde a maior atracção são os golfinhos
reviews/17/text: Wij zijn hier heengereden om pelikanen te spotten. Dat is gelukt: alleen op grote afstand. We zijn wel in heel bijzondere dorpjes terecht gekomen.

reviews/18/text: Un endroit à l'écart du bruit de la civilisation, plus de 260 espèces d'oiseaux répertoriées dans la région, dont certains migrateurs. Une grande biodiversité visible.

reviews/0/text: Setúbal certainly looks beautiful and with the breathtaking bay, where the lush green Arrábida meets the sea, and resident dolphins there is a lot to see and do with young kids. However, there is currently a major dredging of the river underway, which aims to improve access to the port of Setúbal. This will have a negative environmental impact on the city's famous  river and beaches. Beginning in December 2019 the river is being dredged, while the poor resident bottle nosed dolphins are close by. Who knows what effect this will have on the River Sado, home not only to the dolphins but to a diverse range of sealife. Local residents and environmentalists have tried to fight against money focused business groups, but unfortunately their calls to stop the dredging have fallen on deaf ears. So if you were planning to visit this city you might want to give it a miss as its natural beauty is sadly being destroyed as we speak and the famous resident dolphins may soon be no more.
reviews/0/title: Goodbye to the beautiful river Sado
reviews/1/text:
Very nice place, mountain and sea, Sado River and its dalphins! We can enjoy sun, but also the peace of such beautiful places or cross the river to Trois beach.
Restaurants have good fresh fish.
reviews/2/text:
Tiene tantas atracciones y para tantos gustos, que no se deja de admirar sea de día con la mezcla de colores de la naturaleza o de noche con las luces del puerto y sus botes.  

It has so many attractions and for so many tastes, that you can not fail to admire either by day with the mixture of colors of nature or at night with the lights of the port and its boats. You have to know Setúbal.
reviews/3/text: A gorgeous bay which is both a great place to relax and a busy working environment. We stayed in the hills above Setubal and enjoyed wonderful views of the vessels criss crossing the bay, everything from fishing boats and ferries to luxury yachts and bulk carriers. Setubal is a lively but laid back town with a bustling fish market area, intriguing old town and plenty of good places to eat and drink. Across the bay there's manicured modern development in Troia, with wide and empty beaches nearby. One of the highlights of our stay was a morning catamaran cruise to spot dolphin, easily arranged near the docks or book online (Vertigem Azul).
reviews/3/title: Just a short hop from Lisbon, and so much to enjoy
reviews/4/text: Setúbal is member since 2002 to the Club of the Most Beautiful Bays in the World. Be sure to appreciate the beauty of this bay from different perspectives: from Tróis across the river; from Arrábida directly and from Forte de São Filipe, all of them with privileged points of view to the Setúbal bay. And there is an extra feature: wild dolphins in the Sado river. Try to spot them from the beach, from the ferry or take a specific dolphin tour (non-intrusive in the natural environment of the dolphins).
reviews/4/title: One of the most beautiful bays in the world
reviews/5/text: A great place to sail and windsurf. Generally blessd with a "nortade" (northwind) in the afternoon up to 20kts.
reviews/5/title: A paradise for sailing and windsurfing
reviews/6/text: Therre is too much industry around that make the bay to look less pretty that it could. Still on a sunny day you have a nice feeling
reviews/7/text:
PAck your things and get early in the morning to this paradise.
Covered from the wind you will find an amazing beach. COnsider high traffic on weekends and in summer time, arrive early and make sure to bring sunblock and water. You will find nice chairs and umbrella for only 10 euros, its totally worth to enjoy your beach day.
reviews/8/text:
The Setubal Bay belongs from November of 2002 to the restricted club of the most beautiful bays of the world.
This meaning of this club is trying to promote the change of experiences in between the members and this on a political level of protection, conservation to maintain this bays. To the bay belongs also the amazing view of the Serra de Arrábida. And the bay is also the normal habitat of the “roaz-corvineiro” a European Dolphin Community.
reviews/9/text: Vale a pena fazer a Serra da Arrabida para ter algums vistas bonitas. Nada imperdivel, mas se tiver tempo vale a visita.
reviews/9/title: Uma vista linda, mas um rapido passeio
reviews/10/text:
Paisagens deslumbrantes com o oceano por perto. 
Praias paradisíacas, de recantos misteriosos. 
Sitio ideal para quem gosta de caminhadas.
reviews/11/text: Tal vez sea una exageración, pero yo he leído que la baia de Setubal estaba considerada como una delas mejores del mundo. la verdad es que es muy bonita.
reviews/11/title: Considerada una de las mejores baias del mundo.

Si vous connaissez le bassin d'Arcachon, la baie de Setubal a la même configuration avec les dauphins en plus !. La presqu'île du Cap Ferret équivaut ici à celle de Troia. 

La comparaison ne s'arrête pas la puisqu'on y déguste aussi les huitres et les fabuleux vins de région, l'Arabida.

reviews/13/text: Foi um passeio sensacional que fizemos no Rio Sado para apreciar os golfinhos e tivemos oportunidade de conhecer a Baia de Setubal e gostei bastante.
